                <note rend="inline" type="source">819.413 Columbus/19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Panama</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-29T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 29, 1930—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>29. Your despatch No. 37, April 26, 1930. War Department and Governor Panama
                    Canal state they have no objection to immediate removal of Columbus statue from
                    present situation to another point in the Republic of Panama. Accordingly, you
                    will please inform Panamanian Government that this Government agrees to the
                    immediate removal of such statue. Since it appears that the statue is the
                    property of Panama you will avoid creating the impression that the transfer
                    involves a gift from the United States. The Department does not feel that you
                    should suggest to the Panamanian Government that it invite the President-elect
                    of Colombia to attend any celebration which may be held in connection with the
                    transfer, as any suggestion of this kind should originate with the Panamanian
                    Government itself.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
